        <div class=3D"section collapsed" id=3D"section-pre-header-section">=
<div class=3D"section-container"><p>The <strong>Poisson distribution</stron=
g> is the <a href=3D"https://brilliant.org/wiki/discrete-random-variables-d=
efinition/" class=3D"wiki_link" title=3D"discrete probability distribution"=
 target=3D"_blank">discrete probability distribution</a> of the number of e=
vents occurring in a given time period, given the average number of times t=
he event occurs over that time period. </p>

<blockquote class=3D"example"><p>
A certain fast-food restaurant gets an average of 3 visitors to the drive-t=
hrough per minute.  This is just an average, however.  The actual amount ca=
n vary.  </p>

<p>A Poisson distribution can be used to analyze the probability of various=
 events regarding how many customers go through the drive-through.  It can =
allow one to calculate the probability of a lull in activity (when there ar=
e 0 customers coming to the drive-through) as well as the probability of a =
flurry of activity (when there are 5 or more customers coming to the drive-=
through).  This information can, in turn, help a manager plan for these eve=
nts with staffing and scheduling.
</p><!-- end-example --></blockquote>

<p>In addition to its use for staffing and scheduling, the Poisson distribu=
tion also has applications in biology (especially <a href=3D"https://brilli=
ant.org/wiki/mutation-and-dna-repair/" class=3D"wiki_link" title=3D"mutatio=
n" target=3D"_blank">mutation</a> detection), finance, disaster readiness, =
