           =20
                <div class=3D"question-container">
   =20
        <p>Damon is working the evening shift at the register of his retail=
 job. There are currently two registers open, but his coworker is about to =
go home for the day and close her register.</p>

<p>The number of customers approaching each register is an independent Pois=
son random variable. If each register was getting an average of 2 customers=
 per minute, what is the probability that Damon will have more than 4 custo=
mers approaching his register in minute after his coworker goes home?</p>

<p>Round your answer to 3 decimal places.</p>

   =20
</div>
           =20

            <div class=3D"solution-container hide">
                <br><br>
                The correct answer is: <strong>0.371</strong>
               =20
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
<p></p>

<p>Additionally, the Poisson distribution can be thought of as the limiting=
 case of the <a href=3D"https://brilliant.org/wiki/binomial-distribution/" =
class=3D"wiki_link" title=3D"binomial distribution" target=3D"_blank">binom=
ial distribution</a>.  If there are <span><span class=3D"katex"><span class=
=3D"katex-mathml"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><seman=
